Lucia di Lammermoor, Opera Holland Park, review
Rupert Christiansen reviews Lucia di Lammermoor at Opera Holland Park. Lucia di Lammamoor at Opera Holland Park Photo: Alex Brenner,	By Rupert Christiansen
4:28PM BST 08 Jun 2012
Comments
A cracked slate wall and some interlocking panels of steel-meshed fencing form the austere setting of Olivia Fuchs’ production of Donizetti’s masterly melodrama. But what was it trying to tell us exactly? The costuming is firmly illustrative of the 1880s, but the chorus has been supplied with incongruously modern jiving choreography. Characterisation, meanwhile, is rather bland: there’s a hint that Enrico has unspeakable thoughts about his kid sister, but Lucia herself seems very prim and buttoned-up, and not at all the sort of dreamily sensitive girl pushed to the brink of insanity, who would end up stabbing her horrible husband on their wedding night.
My theory is that Fuchs has been wrongfooted by David Alden’s superb version at English National Opera. Alden’s excavation of the text’s implications and creation of a richly brooding and menacing atmosphere has left her interpretation with nowhere to go. What’s she’s done isn’t bad by any means, but it doesn’t have any obvious point or focus.
Stuart Stratford’s conducting of the City of London Sinfonia is much more purposeful DASH sometimes rumbustious to a fault, but always alive and energized. Every note of the score, as far I could determine, was included, and the “authentic” glass harmonica obbligato (played beautifully by Philipp-Alexander Maguerre) replaced the “traditional” flute in the mad scene.
Russian soprano Elvira Fatykhova made her British debut in the title-role. Bravely soldiering on through outbursts of ambient noise from passing aircraft and the chanting of what sounded like a rally of renegade Girl Guides, she proved herself a useful singer.
The voice is small but firm, her pitching accurate and her technique fluent, if hard and shrill of tone at the very top. Appropriately petite of build, she moves well. I just wish she had projected more of the girl’s vulnerability and had allowed her imagination to play over the music: her performance was admirable, but a tad mechanical and uninvolving.
