After Dry January I’m raising a glass or two to February
Avoiding alcohol as part of the Dry January campaign was ago, but hard lessons have been learnt about drinking too much Peter Oborne, who gave up drinking as part of Alcohol Concern's Dry January campaign, said: 'It was agony’
Photo: Clara Molden By Peter Oborne
6:00PM GMT 03 Feb 2013
Follow Comments
I knew Dry January would be hard. But I had not realised quite how hard. It was agony! Arriving home in the evening and pouring myself a mineral water. Going to a party where my hostess tries to ply me with alcoholic drink – and demanding orange juice instead. Dropping into the pub and ordering a coke.
Since I first announced my intention to give up drink for a month in these pages, the time has crawled by. I haven’t just counted the hours, I’ve counted the minutes. I’ve never known a month last so long. At times I felt like I was in prison, being tormented by a sadistic jailer. Thank God for February.
I lapsed on four or five occasions, the first in the first week, most recently over Sunday lunch with the parish council chairman. He served perfectly cooked roast beef. Roast beef needs claret. I’d lapsed the previous evening as well, when friends came to dinner.
On that occasion my reasoning was as follows: I must be a warm and generous host. This isn’t easy if I’m drinking mineral water. Jesus Christ understood this, otherwise he wouldn’t have turned water into wine at the wedding at Cana. (If you read the scriptures carefully, and do the sums, he liberated about seven barrels, equal to 20 gallons.) I convinced myself, I was thinking of others – as He was. My drinking became an altruistic act, to make my guests happy.
