When I tell people that I’ve lapsed five times they say: “You haven’t given up at all.”
This shows a failure of basic understanding. There are 31 days in January. On approximately 26 of them I did not have a drink. Each of these was a day of hardship, mortification and self-denial.
On the upside Dry January left me feeling far more healthy than I have for years. My complexion improved. I slept through the night. My head felt razor sharp in the morning. Those pains in the lower back went. I also lost a remarkable amount of weight.
Staying sober, I started to grasp how boorish and uninteresting even quite sophisticated people become after they’ve had a few drinks. I used to think of alcohol as an aid to conversation; in fact it stands in its way. This is a point grasped by Stalin, who used to love to get his henchmen drunk at banquets. Those in the know would try to bribe the waiters to fill their vodka glasses with water. Alert to these tricks, the Russian dictator would insist on filling glasses himself, forcing victims to join him in a toast. I also managed to get far more work done. Drinking takes up more time than one imagines. It’s not just the hours you spend drinking, but the recovery period. At the end of it all, I’ve had no choice but to admit that I’m an addict. It’s not that I need a drink to get through an average day. I need several. And this slavish dependency has got to end.
From now on, I will endeavour not to return to my previous way of life, which involved a large scotch followed by half a bottle of red wine every evening. I’m going to cut out drinking on my own. I will drink as much as ever with friends in the pub, or over dinner, or at lunch. But alcohol will no longer be something that’s always there. Every week there are going to be three days when I don’t have a drink. This might be harder than I think. But I have been shocked by how difficult I found it giving up booze. Better to cut down now than have to give up altogether later. That would be terrible.
Peter Oborne gave up alcohol as part of Alcohol Concern’s Dry January campaign backed by The Daily Telegraph telegraph.co.uk/healthalcoholconcern.org.uk
